'Local access' is ambiguous. Examples of local access include physical access, authenticated access, or local network access (e.g. RFC1918 subnet). Without this information, the detail in the CVE is close to useless for defenders to use.

A weakness of CVE is the inability to document a 'combined' risk score of two otherwise low/medium risk issues. This CVE description is for not salting (PR: High) and IDOR (presumably, PR: None or PR: Low). As a result, it has a muddled description. Ideally the author documents a *single* issue in a CVE and describes the combined impact elsewhere.
The explicit description of trigger conditions allows even non-technical users to understand the priv requirements.

The use of the term 'privileged user' may be confusing to some readers, but is clear in the context that the PR clarifies that 'High' is for significant control, whereas 'privileged user' can also mean a relatively low level of privileged access.
The description alone doesn't clarify, but if you assume the PR is correct, the combined description + PR is enough to understand the issue in its entirety.

Given that the name of the software is vManage, it is implied that the users of the software are system administrators, and it is unclear about whether there are other non-administrative users, such as end-users, on the system at all.

It is also implied that there will be various access levels within vManage, and that any user on the system (e.g. an administrator of only one managed system, or the super-admin of the vManage instance) can XSS any other user of the system.

So this sounds like 'low' to me.

The CVE description does not contain enough information to determine where a trust boundary might be crossed. It is implied that it is an escalation from administrator of the main system to code execution within a secure enclave, which is something that is never supposed to be possible. So 'high' seems justified.
Seems pretty clear; Subscriber implies a low level of privilege, perhaps even available to anyone in the world upon request.
SOGo is not something I've ever heard of, and this sentence does nothing to make clear what level of access is typically needed to upload things to it.
As a library, ImageMagick has no control of when its functions are made available to users; the authors have done the right thing and assumed the worst case.

It is implied that the product is a multi-user product with varying permission levels, and any permission level is sufficient to exploit a known IDOR (that was a different CVE). IMO, this should have been 'low'
Based on the context of the product being a consumer router, which is a single-user system, I'm quite surprised to see 'low' privileges required. I would expect either 'none' or 'high'.
